            <div type="general">
               <head>General</head>
               <p>The Šarqiyya region is a governorate in Northeastern Egypt. It is a 
                   primarily agricultural and industrial region that takes pride in the 
                   pure-bred Arabian horses that adorn its flag. Among the crops that 
                   grow in the Šarqiyya are cotton, maize, rice and wheat.</p>
            </div>
             
             <div type="researchHistory">
               <head>Research history</head>
                 <p>The Šarqiyya dialects belong to the Delta group of the Egyptian dialects 
                     but exhibit traits that connects them with the Palestinian and Bedouin 
                     dialects. <rs type="bibl" ref="zotid:S26Q4Z2Y">Abul-Fadl 1961</rs> is a study in dialect geography on the Šarqiyya 
                     region that discusses phonology and some aspects of morphology. 
                     <rs type="bibl" ref="zotid:FTI6A9GV">Woidich 1979</rs> and <rs type="bibl" ref="zotid:ZR6HIC63">1980</rs> on the dialect of ˁAwāmra complements it with a 
                     discussion of morphology and also offers an ethno-lexicographical part.</p>
                 <p>Texts from it-Tallēn, Ṣanafa and il-ˁAwāmra are available in <rs type="bibl" ref="zotid:MCMLVLRI">Behnstedt and 
                     Woidich’s 1987</rs> <hi rendition="#i">Die ägyptisch-arabischen Dialekte</hi>, volume 3, part 1, and 
                     data on the Šarqiyya region is included in the other volumes of this work.</p>
             </div>

            <div type="dictionaries">
               <head>Dictionaries</head>
                <p>Lexical data from the Šarqiyya is included in the glossaries (Arabic-German and German-Arabic) 
                    published by P. Behnstedt and M. Woidich (<rs type="bibl" ref="zotid:SIGLEM5B">Behnstedt &amp; Woidich 1994</rs>; <rs type="bibl" ref="zotid:Z4KGUBTB">Behnstedt &amp; Woidich 1999</rs>).</p>
            </div>
            
